<meta name="socialpost1" content="A review of World Cup contracts host cities signed with FIFA shows that almost all of the costs for organizing the tournament fall on the cities, whose ability to collect revenue is limited. In Texas, that could leave taxpayers on the hook." />
<meta name="socialpost2" content="Eleven U.S. cities will host World Cup games this summer, which is expected to generate $11B for FIFA. The cities get little in return. They do not see a slice of game-day revenues from ticket sales, concessions and merchandise, or parking." />
<meta name="socialpost3" content="As the World Cup nears, some host cities are questioning whether their agreements with FIFA will leave them paying for more than they get in return. “Everybody signed an agreement that was very, very one-sided,” said an LA host committee member." />
<meta name="socialpost4" content="The @houstonchron reviewed some of the 2026 World Cup host cities’ contracts with FIFA. The contracts show that almost all of the costs for organizing the tournament fall on the cities, whose ability to collect revenue is limited." />
<meta name="socialpost5" content="The secretive contracts between FIFA and U.S. World Cup host cities offer few details about costs to taxpayers. “These cities are going to invest a lot of money in hosting FIFA, and the people who are paying for that should know,” one expert said." />
